		<img width="2000" height="960" src="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-skutik-dam.jpg" class="singlepostthumb wp-post-image" alt="alewives" decoding="async" fetchpriority="high" srcset="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-skutik-dam.jpg 2000w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-skutik-dam-520x250.jpg 520w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-skutik-dam-1200x576.jpg 1200w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-skutik-dam-768x369.jpg 768w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-skutik-dam-1536x737.jpg 1536w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-skutik-dam-900x432.jpg 900w" sizes="(max-width: 2000px) 100vw, 2000px" /><div class="post-thumbnail-caption">Alewives congregate in a fishway on the St. Croix River, known as the Skutik River by local First Nations, which straddles Maine and New Brunswick. A series of dams on the river block the fishes’ passage from the Atlantic Ocean to spawning grounds upriver. Years of restoration efforts, and the removal of a dam, may soon see the alewives restored across their habitat. Photo by Robert F. Bukaty/AP Images</div>
			<article class="main container col4">
								<header class="maincol">
										<h1 class="pagetitle">Dammed But Not Doomed</h1>
										<h2 class="dek singlepagecontainer">As dams come down on the Skutik River, the once-demonized alewife—a fish beloved by the Passamaquoddy—gets a second chance at life.</h2>
										<section class="singlebyline singlepagecontainer">
						<h3 class="invis">Authored by</h3>
						by  
										<a href="https://hakaimagazine.com/profiles/moira-donovan/" class="tagmanager" id="author_link_top" >Moira Donovan</a>								<br/>
												</section>
					 
					<aside class="singlebydatewords singlepagecontainer">
